---
import Layout from '../../layouts/Layout.astro';
import { DOMAIN } from '../../data/site';

const title = "The Science of Body Recomposition - Build Muscle & Lose Fat | BodyCompOS";
const description = "Learn how to build muscle and lose body fat simultaneously. Read about the physiological mechanisms, caloric parity, protein distribution, and training guidelines.";
const canonical = `${DOMAIN}/guides/body-recomposition`;

const schema = {
	'@context': 'https://schema.org',
	'@type': 'Article',
	headline: title,
	description: description,
	datePublished: '2026-06-25',
	dateModified: '2026-06-25',
	author: {
		'@type': 'Organization',
		name: 'BodyCompOS Editorial Board',
	},
	publisher: {
		'@type': 'Organization',
		name: 'BodyCompOS',
		logo: {
			'@type': 'ImageObject',
			url: `${DOMAIN}/favicon.svg`,
		},
	},
};
---

<Layout title={title} description={description} canonical={canonical} schema={[schema]}>
	<section class="site-container py-10 sm:py-12">
		<!-- Breadcrumbs -->
		<nav class="flex mb-6 text-xs font-semibold text-muted-foreground gap-2" aria-label="Breadcrumb">
			<a class="hover:text-accent transition-colors" href="/">Home</a>
			<span>/</span>
			<a class="hover:text-accent transition-colors" href="/guides">Guides</a>
			<span>/</span>
			<span class="text-foreground">Body Recomposition</span>
		</nav>

		<!-- Content Hero -->
		<div class="max-w-3xl">
			<p class="eyebrow">Scientific Guide</p>
			<h1 class="mt-3 text-4xl font-black leading-tight sm:text-5xl text-foreground">
				The Science of Body Recomposition <br/>
				<span class="text-success bg-gradient-to-r from-success to-accent bg-clip-text text-transparent">Lose Fat & Build Muscle Concurrently</span>
			</h1>
			<p class="mt-5 text-lg leading-relaxed text-muted-foreground">
				Body recomposition challenges the traditional view that fat loss and muscle gain must be separated into distinct cut and bulk phases. This guide explains the metabolic pathways that support body recomposition.
			</p>
		</div>

		<!-- Main editorial body -->
		<div class="mt-10 max-w-4xl grid gap-8 lg:grid-cols-[1fr_300px]">
			<div class="content-panel bg-card border border-border p-6 sm:p-8 rounded-2xl">
				<div class="prose-lite space-y-8 text-sm text-muted-foreground leading-relaxed">
					
					<section>
						<h2 class="text-xl font-bold text-foreground mb-3">1. Physiological Mechanisms</h2>
						<p>
							Body recomposition is possible because muscle hypertrophy and adipose lipolysis are controlled by different physiological systems. Adipose reduction is a response to negative system-wide energy balance, where your body mobilizes stored fatty acids to meet energy needs. 
						</p>
						<p class="mt-3">
							Muscle building, however, is a localized cellular response driven by resistance training stimulus, amino acid availability, and intracellular signaling pathways like mTOR (mammalian target of rapamycin). When mechanical tension from resistance training is combined with a consistent supply of amino acids, muscle protein synthesis (MPS) can occur even in a slight caloric deficit. The energy required for muscle growth is supplied by fat oxidation.
						</p>
					</section>

					<section>
						<h2 class="text-xl font-bold text-foreground mb-3">2. Optimal Candidates for Recomposition</h2>
						<p>
							While possible, body recomposition is highly optimized for specific groups of lifters:
						</p>
						<ul class="space-y-2 mt-3 pl-5 list-disc">
							<li><strong>Beginner Lifters:</strong> Beginners have a high sensitivity to resistance training, allowing for rapid muscle growth and fat loss.</li>
							<li><strong>Detrained Individuals:</strong> People returning to lifting benefit from muscle memory, quickly rebuilding lost muscle tissue while burning fat.</li>
							<li><strong>High Body Fat Lifters:</strong> Individuals with higher body fat have a large reserve of stored energy, which can support muscle building during a deficit.</li>
						</ul>
					</section>

					<section>
						<h2 class="text-xl font-bold text-foreground mb-3">3. Caloric Parity and Macronutrient Targets</h2>
						<p>
							To recompose effectively, your daily calorie intake should be near maintenance—either a slight deficit (-2% to -5%) or absolute parity. This energy balance provides enough fuel for recovery and training performance without triggering fat storage.
						</p>
						<p class="mt-3">
							Protein is the most important macronutrient for recomposition. According to the International Society of Sports Nutrition (ISSN), daily protein should be set at the higher end of the spectrum, between **1.8 and 2.2 g per kilogram of body weight** (0.82 to 1.0 g/lb), to support muscle building and manage hunger.
						</p>
					</section>

					<section>
						<h2 class="text-xl font-bold text-foreground mb-3">4. Reassessment Standards</h2>
						<p>
							Since scale weight often remains flat during body recomposition, do not use the scale as your only measure of progress. Instead, track waist circumference (measured at the navel) and progressive strength increases in your lifts. A decreasing waist circumference alongside increasing strength is a clear indicator of successful recomposition. Reassess your strategy every 4 to 6 weeks.
						</p>
					</section>

					<!-- YMYL Disclaimer -->
					<div class="border-t border-border pt-6 text-[10px] text-muted-foreground">
						<p><strong>YMYL Disclaimer:</strong> This guide is for educational purposes only. Body recomposition involves metabolic adaptations. Individuals with pre-existing metabolic or hormonal conditions should consult a qualified physician before initiating high-protein diets or intensive training programs.</p>
					</div>

				</div>
			</div>
			
			<!-- Sidebar -->
			<div class="space-y-6">
				<div class="surface border border-border p-5 rounded-2xl">
					<h3 class="font-bold text-sm text-foreground">Strategic Tools</h3>
					<p class="text-xs text-muted-foreground mt-2">Calculate your recomposition calories and macros using our tool.</p>
					<a href="/calculators/body-recomposition-calculator" class="button-primary w-full text-center text-xs mt-4 block">Recomp Calculator</a>
				</div>

				<div class="surface border border-border p-5 rounded-2xl">
					<h3 class="font-bold text-sm text-foreground">Related Guides</h3>
					<div class="mt-3 space-y-2 text-xs">
						<a href="/guides/should-i-cut-or-bulk" class="block text-accent hover:underline">Cut or Bulk Matrix</a>
						<a href="/guides/protein-nutrition" class="block text-accent hover:underline">Protein Intake Standards</a>
						<a href="/guides/maintenance-calories" class="block text-accent hover:underline font-semibold">TDEE & Basal Rate</a>
					</div>
				</div>
			</div>
		</div>
	</section>
</Layout>
